## .NET 8 Migration: `EventProcessor`

### Critical Issues in the Original Code

| Issue | .NET 8 Impact |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** — removed entirely |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | Works but deprecated pattern; unreliable for `ManualResetEvent.WaitOne()` |
| `ManualResetEvent` + `Queue` + `lock` | Race condition: multiple enqueues, only one dequeue per signal |
| No cancellation support | Modern .NET uses `CancellationToken` cooperatively |

### Race Condition Bug (exists in original too)

Two rapid `Enqueue` calls → `Set()` called twice, but `WaitOne/Reset` only unblocks once → **second item stuck in queue** until a third enqueue arrives.

---

### Migrated Code (.NET 8)

Replace the entire manual synchronization with `Channel<T>`, the modern high-performance async producer/consumer primitive:

```csharp
using System.Threading.Channels;

public class EventProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private Task? _processingTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _processingTask = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken ct)
    {
        try
        {
            await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(ct))
            {
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException)
        {
            // Normal shutdown — drain remaining items if desired
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        if (!_channel.Writer.TryWrite(item))
            throw new InvalidOperationException("Channel is closed.");
    }

    public async ValueTask StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        if (_cts is null || _processingTask is null) return;

        _channel.Writer.Complete();          // signal no more items
        _cts.CancelAfter(timeout ?? TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5)); // hard deadline

        try
        {
            await _processingTask;           // wait for drain or cancellation
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException)
        {
            // Timed out — loop was cancelled
        }
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        await StopAsync();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item)
    {
        // your processing logic
    }
}
```

### If you need a synchronous `Stop()` (non-async caller)

```csharp
public void Stop()
{
    StopAsync().AsTask().GetAwaiter().GetResult();
}
```

---

### Key Migration Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Guidance |
|---|---|
| **`Thread.Abort()` → exception** | Use `CancellationToken` for cooperative cancellation. There is no replacement for `Abort()`. |
| **Blocking in async code** | Don't call `.Result` or `.Wait()` on hot paths — it can deadlock with `SynchronizationContext`. |
| **`Channel` backpressure** | Use `CreateBounded<T>(capacity)` if producers can outrun consumers; `TryWrite` returns `false` when full. |
| **Exception swallowing** | The original silently dies on any `Handle()` exception. Add a `try/catch` inside the loop if you want resilience. |
| **`Thread.IsBackground`** | Original thread keeps the process alive. `Task.Run` uses thread-pool (background) threads — the app can exit while processing. Use `StopAsync()` in your shutdown path. |
| **Ordering guarantees** | `Channel<T>` is FIFO — same as `Queue<T>`. Safe. |

### Minimal-Change Alternative (if you can't restructure)

If you must keep the thread-based shape, at minimum replace the broken shutdown:

```csharp
private volatile bool _stopping;
private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();

public void Stop()
{
    _stopping = true;
    _cts.Cancel();
    if (!_thread.Join(5000))
    {
        // Log warning — thread did not exit.
        // Thread.Abort() does NOT exist. You cannot force-kill it.
    }
}
```

The `Channel<T>` approach is strongly recommended — it eliminates the race condition, the manual locking, and the unsafe shutdown in one move.
